# Evaluation function
def evaluate_model(history,X_test,y_test,model):
    scores = model.evaluate((X_test),y_test, verbose=0)
    print("Accuracy: %.2f%%" % (scores[1]*100))
    
    print(history)
    fig1, ax_acc = plt.subplots()
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.title('Model - Accuracy')
    plt.legend(['Training', 'Validation'], loc='lower right')
    plt.show()
    
    fig2, ax_loss = plt.subplots()
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.title('Model- Loss')
    plt.legend(['Training', 'Validation'], loc='upper right')
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.show()
    target_names=['1','2', '3']
    
    y_true=[]
    for element in y_test:
        y_true.append(np.argmax(element))
    prediction_proba=model.predict(X_test)
    prediction=np.argmax(prediction_proba,axis=1)
    cnf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_true, prediction)
    return cnf_matrix,(scores[1]*100)
    
print("Done")

from keras.layers import Dense, Convolution1D, MaxPool1D, Flatten, Dropout
from keras.layers import BatchNormalization
from keras.activations import softmax
def network(X_train,y_train):
    im_shape=(X_train.shape[1],1)
    inputs_cnn=Input(shape=(im_shape), name='inputs_cnn')
    
    #First convolution layer
    conv1d = Convolution1D(64,kernel_size=6)(inputs_cnn)
    batchNorm = BatchNormalization()(conv1d)
    maxPool = MaxPool1D(pool_size=2)(batchNorm)
    #Second Convolution layer
    conv1d2 = Convolution1D(128,kernel_size=3)(maxPool)
    batchNorm2 = BatchNormalization()(conv1d2)
    maxPool2 = MaxPool1D(pool_size=2,strides=2,padding='same')(batchNorm2)
    
    #flatten layer
    flat = Flatten()(maxPool2)
    
    #Dense Layers
    dense = Dense(64)(flat)
    dense1 = Dense(21)(dense)
    
    #output
    main_output= Dense(3,activation='softmax')(dense1)
    
    
    
    model = Model(inputs= inputs_cnn, outputs=main_output)
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',metrics = ['accuracy'])

    return(model)
model = network(data_train,label_train)
print(model.summary())

from keras.layers import Dense, Convolution1D, MaxPool1D, Flatten, Dropout
from keras.layers import BatchNormalization
def network_LSTM(X_train,y_train):
    im_shape=(X_train.shape[1],1)
    inputs_lstm=Input(shape=(im_shape), name='inputs_lstm')
    #Dense Layer
    dense = Dense(32)(inputs_lstm)
    #LSTM
    lstm = LSTM(128)(dense)
    #Dropout
    drop = Dropout(0.2)(lstm)
    #batch_norm
    bNorm = BatchNormalization()(drop)
    #dense
    dense1 = Dense(64)(bNorm)
    
    #dropout 1
    drop1 = Dropout(0.2)(dense1)
    #Batch_norm 1
    bNorm1 = BatchNormalization()(drop1)
    #Output
    main_output = Dense(3,activation='softmax')(bNorm1)
    

    model = Model(inputs= inputs_lstm, outputs=main_output)
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',metrics = ['accuracy'])
    
    return(model)
model = network_LSTM(data_train,label_train)
print(model.summary())

from keras.layers import Dense, Convolution1D, MaxPool1D, Flatten, Dropout
from keras.layers import BatchNormalization
def network_CNN_LSTM(X_train,y_train):
    im_shape=(X_train.shape[1],1)
    inputs_cnn_lstm=Input(shape=(im_shape), name='inputs_cnn_lstm')
    
    #Conv1d,batchnorm, maxpooling
    conv = Convolution1D(64,kernel_size=6)(inputs_cnn_lstm)
    batchNorm = BatchNormalization()(conv)
    maxPool = MaxPool1D(pool_size=2,strides=2,padding='same')(batchNorm)
    
    #Conv1d,batchnorm, maxpooling
    conv1 = Convolution1D(64,kernel_size=3)(maxPool)
    batchNorm1 = BatchNormalization()(conv1)
    maxPool1 = MaxPool1D(pool_size=2)(batchNorm1)
    
    #LSTM
    lstm = LSTM(128)(maxPool1)
    
    #Flatten
    flat = Flatten()(lstm)
    
    #Dense Layers
    dense = Dense(64)(flat)
    dense1 = Dense(32)(dense)
    
    #Output
    main_output = Dense(3,activation='softmax')(dense1)
    
    

    
    model = Model(inputs=inputs_cnn_lstm, outputs=main_output)
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',metrics = ['accuracy'])
    
    return(model)
model=network_CNN_LSTM(data_train,label_train)
print(model.summary())

## Note: Subtracted 2 from each of the labels

The way Keras handles labels makes it easy for it to handle labels like 0,1,2 like we used in problem 2. However, because the labels in problem 3 are 2,3,4 we will need to convert them to 0,1,2. We do this by subtracting 2 from each of the labels. This has to do with the sparse_crossentropy loss function needing the labels to start from 0. 


## Analysis of Performance

Based on the plots above, and the accuracy metrics it is clear that the last model performed just as well as the model trained on the previous dataset as expected. Since the dataset that we are giving it is basically the same (all we are changing is the end labels) this result is expected. We can see that the model also uses the same sort of trick where it tries to simply guess the output as 0 every time.

However, based on the confusion matrix it is quite clear what all the models are doing here: they are simply guessing a label of 0 since it will generally be the correct answer most of the time(as can be seen by the unique counts displayed above as well as on the confusion matrix). In order to get more generalizable results (applicability beyond this dataset) it is clear that either new data points need to be added (collected manually) or some method needs to be developed to generate random data that is still uses the same underlying distribution. For example, in image processing rotating images is a common way to increase generalizability as well as increase the number of images that a model can train on.
